Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in NIL (Not In Link) prediction for entity linking lies in the model’s ability to distinguish between true entities in the knowledge base and mentions that either refer to non-existent (missing) entities or are not entities at all (non-entity phrases), as highlighted in Paper 2. Current models, even those leveraging powerful pretrained language models, tend to overfit to known entities due to imbalanced training signals—where non-NIL examples dominate—leading to poor generalization on NIL cases. While structured prediction (Paper 1) and LLM prompting (Paper 3) offer promising directions, they do not directly address the representational conflict between NIL and non-NIL instances during training. My intuition is that instead of treating NIL as a residual class, we should explicitly disentangle the semantic representations of mention-context pairs based on their *linkability status*. This can be achieved through a meta-contrastive learning framework that operates on two levels: (1) intra-instance contrast between candidate entities and a dynamic NIL prototype, and (2) inter-instance contrast across batches to sharpen the boundary between linkable and non-linkable mentions. By decoupling the representation learning objective from the final linking decision via a disentangled architecture, we allow the model to learn robust, calibrated confidence for NIL prediction without being biased by frequent non-NIL patterns. This approach differs fundamentally from prior work: unlike SpEL’s aggregation strategy or OneNet’s prompting logic, it introduces an architectural inductive bias toward uncertainty awareness. It also goes beyond simple data augmentation or rebalancing by embedding meta-level contrastive signals into the training dynamics. The result is a system that doesn’t just “learn to not link” but learns *why* not to link, improving both accuracy and interpretability.

